response:
To find the length of the string, we can treat the cylindrical post as a rectangle when it is "unrolled." The width of this rectangle will be the circumference of the base of the cylinder, and the height will be the height of the cylinder. The string will form a straight line on this rectangle, and we can use the Pythagorean theorem to find its length. </think> <answer>Let's use the given information: the circumference is 4 feet, and the height is 12 feet. The string wraps around the post 4 times, so the total horizontal distance traveled by the string is the circumference multiplied by the number of wraps: 4 feet/wrap * 4 wraps = 16 feet. This forms one side of a right triangle, and the height of the post forms the other side. The length of the string is the hypotenuse of this right triangle. Using the Pythagorean theorem, the length of the string \( L \) is given by: \[
L = \sqrt{(16 \text{ feet})^2 + (12 \text{ feet})^2} = \sqrt{256 + 144} = \sqrt{400} = 20 \text{ feet}
\] </answer>

